\date{\today}
\begin{abstract}
We report that the well-known equivalence between the fluctuation-dissipation theorem, the detailed-balance, and the absence of heat dissipation in a steady state does not hold, in general. It is shown that the fluctuation-dissipation theorem and the detailed-balance become mutually exclusive as soon as a velocity-dependent force is involved. A different relation among the three conditions is proposed, which is illustrated with a few example systems. It turns out that any of the three conditions, alone, cannot be an identifier of equilibrium, in general.
\end{abstract}

\pacs{02.50.-r, 05.40.-a, 05.70.Ln}





\maketitle

The fluctuation-dissipation theorem (FDT) is an identity between the linear response and the associated correlation function, which holds in equilibrium (EQ)~\cite{ER,JN,fdt50,marconi2008}. Recently, it is reported~\cite{Sekimoto,Harada2005,Harada2006} that a violation of FDT leads to heat dissipation into the reservoir, and thus characterizes a non-equilibrium (NEQ) steady state. The detailed balance (DB)~\cite{gardiner,Hatano2001,Speck2005} condition of the probability-current balance between any pair of states was known to be another property of EQ. It turns out that the DB is equivalent to the condition of no heat dissipation in a steady state (NHD)~\cite{Crooks1998,Kurchan1998,Oono1998,Speck2005,Hatano2001}.
These findings show the equivalence between the three conditions (FDT, DB, and NHD) and imply positive heat dissipation if any of them is violated. This non-negativity of heat dissipation is regarded as a fundamental measure for the NEQ steady state~\cite{Sekimoto,Harada2005}.


Meanwhile, it has been reported that the DB and the NHD conditions may not be equivalent in the presence of velocity-dependent forces~\cite{Kim0407,SF2012,Lee2013,GC,Hao2014,Kwon2015}. Thus, the equivalence relation among the three conditions may not hold in general, and the role of heat dissipation as a measure of irreversibility should be re-examined. In particular, the velocity-dependent force is a characteristics of the so-called ``active matter systems''~\cite{GC,ams,ams2}, which have attracted a lot of interests recently. Therefore, it is imperative and also timely to re-examine the three conditions and their inter-relations when a velocity-dependent force is involved.


In this study, we demonstrate that, in the presence of velocity-dependent forces, (i) the FDT and the DB are mutually exclusive, (ii) the FDT guarantees the NHD, but not vice versa, and (iii) heat dissipation in a steady state is not a measure of irreversibility (DB violation). We derive a fluctuation-response relation for heat dissipation, from which we can deduce a classification diagram for steady states of Langevin systems [Fig.~\ref{diag}(b)]. We remark that our heat-dissipation relation is based on the response and correlation functions of position, while the original work by Harada and Sasa~\cite{Harada2005,Harada2006} was based on those of velocity not well-defined in the overdamped limit~\cite{singularity}. To illustrate our results, we study a few example systems explicitly.
